## 🚀 Getting Started

### Prerequisites

Make sure you have the following installed:

* [.NET 8 SDK](https://dotnet.microsoft.com/download/dotnet/8.0)
* [Node.js](https://nodejs.org/)
* SQL Server
* An AWS account
* An AWS Cognito User Pool
* An Amazon S3 bucket

You will also need AWS credentials configured locally if you are running the API outside AWS.

---

# 🔧 Backend Setup

Navigate to the API directory:

```bash
cd demo-api
```

Restore the .NET dependencies:

```bash
dotnet restore
```

## Configure SQL Server

Update the connection string in `appsettings.json`:

```json
{
  "ConnectionStrings": {
    "DefaultConnection": "YOUR_SQL_SERVER_CONNECTION_STRING"
  }
}
```

## Configure AWS S3

Configure your S3 bucket:

```json
{
  "S3Settings": {
    "Region": "us-east-1",
    "BucketName": "YOUR_S3_BUCKET_NAME"
  }
}
```

The API stores uploaded book covers in S3 and saves the corresponding S3 object key in the database.

Book cover images are returned to the frontend through temporary pre-signed URLs.

## Configure AWS Cognito

Configure your Cognito User Pool and App Client:

```json
{
  "JwtBearer": {
    "Authority": "YOUR_COGNITO_ISSUER",
    "MetadataAddress": "YOUR_COGNITO_OPENID_CONFIGURATION_URL"
  },
  "AWS": {
    "Cognito": {
      "ClientId": "YOUR_COGNITO_CLIENT_ID",
      "ClientSecret": "YOUR_COGNITO_CLIENT_SECRET"
    }
  }
}
```

> **Important:** Never commit real AWS credentials, Cognito client secrets, database passwords, or other sensitive configuration values to source control.

For local development, consider using user secrets, environment variables, or another secure secrets management solution.

## Run Database Migrations

Apply the Entity Framework Core migrations:

```bash
dotnet ef database update
```

If the EF Core CLI tool is not installed:

```bash
dotnet tool install --global dotnet-ef
```

## Run the API

Start the backend:

```bash
dotnet run
```

The API will be available at the URL shown in the terminal.

Swagger is available when running in the Development environment.

---

# 🎨 Frontend Setup

Open a new terminal and navigate to the frontend:

```bash
cd frontend
```

Install dependencies:

```bash
npm install
```

Start the development server:

```bash
npm run dev
```

The Vite development server will provide the URL for the frontend application.

## Available Scripts

### Start development server

```bash
npm run dev
```

### Build for production

```bash
npm run build
```

### Preview production build

```bash
npm run preview
```

### Run ESLint

```bash
npm run lint
```

## 🔐 Authentication Flow

Authentication is handled using **AWS Cognito**.

The general authentication flow is:

```text
User
 │
 │ Sign Up / Sign In
 ▼
React Frontend
 │
 │ POST /api/auth/signin
 ▼
ASP.NET Core API
 │
 │ AWS SDK
 ▼
AWS Cognito
 │
 │ Access Token
 │ Refresh Token
 ▼
ASP.NET Core API
 │
 │ JWT
 ▼
React Frontend
```

Once authenticated, the frontend sends the access token with requests to protected endpoints:

```http
Authorization: Bearer <access-token>
```

The Books API is protected using JWT Bearer authentication.

## 📚 API Endpoints

### Authentication

| Method | Endpoint            | Description             |
| ------ | ------------------- | ----------------------- |
| `POST` | `/api/auth/signup`  | Register a new user     |
| `POST` | `/api/auth/signin`  | Sign in a user          |
| `POST` | `/api/auth/refresh` | Refresh an access token |
| `POST` | `/api/auth/signout` | Revoke a refresh token  |

### Books

All book endpoints require authentication.

| Method   | Endpoint          | Description       |
| -------- | ----------------- | ----------------- |
| `GET`    | `/api/books`      | Get all books     |
| `GET`    | `/api/books/{id}` | Get a book by ID  |
| `POST`   | `/api/books`      | Create a new book |
| `PUT`    | `/api/books/{id}` | Update a book     |
| `DELETE` | `/api/books/{id}` | Delete a book     |

### Creating a Book

The create endpoint accepts `multipart/form-data` so that book information and an optional cover image can be submitted together.

Example fields:

```text
Title
Author
YearPublished
Poster
```

The cover image is uploaded to Amazon S3 and the S3 object key is stored with the book record.

## 🖼️ Book Cover Storage

Book cover images are stored in Amazon S3 rather than directly in the SQL Server database.

When a book is created:

```text
React Frontend
      │
      │ Upload cover
      ▼
ASP.NET Core API
      │
      │ Upload image
      ▼
Amazon S3
      │
      │ Return object key
      ▼
SQL Server
      │
      │ Store PosterKey
      ▼
Book Record
```

When books are retrieved, the API generates a temporary **pre-signed URL** for each cover image.

This allows the S3 bucket to remain private while still allowing authenticated users to view book covers.

## ☁️ AWS Lambda

The ASP.NET Core API includes support for running on AWS Lambda using:

```text
Amazon.Lambda.AspNetCoreServer.Hosting
```

The API is configured with:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddAWSLambdaHosting(LambdaEventSource.HttpApi);
```

This allows the API to be deployed as a serverless application and exposed through an HTTP API.

A possible production architecture is:

```text
React Frontend
      │
      ▼
API Gateway
      │
      ▼
AWS Lambda
      │
      ├──────────────► AWS Cognito
      │
      ├──────────────► Amazon S3
      │
      └──────────────► SQL Server
```

## 🔒 Security Considerations

Before deploying this application to production:

* Do not commit Cognito client secrets to Git.
* Do not commit database credentials to Git.
* Store secrets using environment variables or AWS Secrets Manager.
* Keep the S3 bucket private.
* Use IAM policies with the minimum required permissions.
* Use HTTPS in production.
* Configure appropriate CORS policies.
* Consider validating uploaded file types and file sizes.
* Use production-specific configuration instead of development settings.
* Rotate exposed credentials immediately if they have ever been committed to a public repository.

